******
[3] Egypt's concerns
Date: Wed 16 Oct 2019
Source: MBS News/sputnik [abridged, edited]
https://www.mbs.news/2019/10/rift-valley-fever-is-the-most-serious-disease-common-to-animals-and-humans.html


Sudan's announcement of outbreaks of "Rift Valley fever" in some states of Sudan has raised serious concerns in neighboring countries that import live cattle from Sudan and raised alertness among quarantine and control agencies in Egypt for fear of transmission of the disease, which resulted in a disaster in 1977 [in Egypt].

Dr. Ibrahim El-Bendary, (formerly) director of preventive medicine at the Egyptian Veterinary Services Authority (formerly) told Sputnik that since Egypt started importing cattle from Sudan, the disease has spread to us in 1977. It was 1st reported in the southernmost province of Aswan and caused significant losses in livestock. At the time, it was equivalent to 82 million pounds, and there were cases of human deaths and injuries, where the injuries amounted to 18 000 cases, while the number of deaths was about 518. The disease is transmitted between humans and animals through mosquitoes and insects, and symptoms of the disease appear in the animal in 2 forms, namely abortions and, in the most severe form, the death of young animals.

Dr. Youssef Mamdouh, (formerly) head of the Central Reservation Department in the Veterinary Services, told Sputnik that when RVF emerges in any of the countries from which live livestock are imported, the animals should be quarantined, sampled, subsequently vaccinated, and kept for 3 weeks before being sent to their destination. He told Sputnik that in 2009 Egypt stopped importing livestock from Sudan because of the emergence of the disease. All quarantine procedures are to be applied in the territory of the exporting country, not in the importing country. It affects all types of livestock, including camels.

The Egyptian Ministry of Agriculture and Land Reclamation announced that all precautionary measures were taken after the media circulated on the suspicion of cases of Rift Valley cattle disease in the northeastern areas of Sudan, which caused the death and stress of some cattle.

