******
[4] Sudan discontinues exports of livestock
Date: Thu 17 Oct 2019
Source: Khartoum Electronic Media Centre [edited]
http://www.en.khartoumcenter.com/animal-resources-ministry-names-a-committee-to-probe-into-water-related-diseases/


The newly appointed minister of Animal Resources, Alam al-Din Abdalla, on Wednesday [16 Oct 2019] named an urgent committee to probe into emergence of water-related diseases on animals and man. "We've banned export of livestock until newly emerged cases of Rift Valley fever are handled," the minister said in statements.

The ministry's undersecretary, according to SUNA [Sudan News Agency], pointed to some Rift Valley cases in Red Sea and River Nile states estimated at 10-15 heads of goats, confirming that all these cases have been dealt with in collaboration with World Health Organization-Animal.

[Byline: Khalid Mohamed]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Sudan is a major exporter of live animals, mainly sheep and goats (Ref 1). In 2017, this export's value was more than USD 476 million; most of the export is destined for Saudi Arabia and the Gulf States. There is also export of camels, most of them going on the hoof to Egypt and Libya.

The transparency exercised during the current event by Sudan's Ministry of Health and the decision of the Agriculture Ministry to temporarily discontinue animal exports has, not surprisingly, met opposition, mainly by the economically involved parties (https://www.assayha.net/now/archives/18575/18575, in Arabic). The export-ban decision may, in the long run, positively contribute to the maintenance of uninterrupted exports, provided measures, in particular control upon intranational animal movements, and preventive mass vaccinations in hitherto not-infected regions, are undertaken at the earliest while consignments are certified in line with OIE's prescribed requirements.

FAO has advised veterinary services and livestock farmers' communities in Sudan, South Sudan, Djibouti, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Burundi, Rwanda, Somalia, Uganda, and United Republic of Tanzania to remain vigilant to the potential occurrence and spread of RVF in humans and/or animals. Egypt, Libya, Chad, Democratic Republic of Congo, Central African Republic, as well as Saudi Arabia and Yemen are also considered at risk of occurrence. The Egyptian 1977 disastrous RVF event should be kept in mind; it demonstrated how RVF-virgin regions may get infected when the virus is introduced, most probably by viraemic animals, into ecologically "receptive" regions when suitable environmental conditions for the RVF vector amplification prevail.

Reference
Wilson RT. Livestock in the Republic of the Sudan: Policies, production, problems and possibilities. Anim Husb Dairy Vet Sci. 2018; 2(3): 1-12. doi: 10.15761/AHDVS.1000142. https://www.oatext.com/pdf/AHDVS-2-142.pdf.
- Mod.AS

